body {background-color: powderblue;}
</style>
<p style="background-color:Tomato;"></p>
<!--This is the title -->
<header>
<h1 style="font-family:Young Serif;">The Research Helper</h1>
<h2>The tool for all your research needs</h2>
<h2> "This is awesome"-Literally no one </h2>
</header>
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">

<div>
<style>
body {font-family: Arial;}

/* Style the tab */
.tab {
  overflow: hidden;
  border: 1px solid #ccc;
  background-color: #f1f1f1;
}

/* Style the buttons inside the tab */
.tab button {
  background-color: #FFFFFF;
  float: left;
  border: none;
  outline: none;
  cursor: pointer;
  padding: 14px 16px;
  transition: 0.3s;
  font-size: 17px;
}

/* Change background color of buttons on hover */
.tab button:hover {
  background-color: #f1f1f1;
}

/* Create an active/current tablink class */
.tab button.active {
  background-color: #ccc;
}

/* Style the tab content */
.tabcontent {
  display: none;
  padding: 6px 12px;
  border: 1px solid #ccc;
  border-top: none;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="tab">
  <button class="tablinks" onclick="openCity(event, 'Sources')">Sources</button>
  <button class="tablinks" onclick="openCity(event, '4 Checks')">4 Checks</button>
  <button class="tablinks" onclick="openCity(event, 'Crediting')">Crediting</button>
</div>

<div id="Sources" class="tabcontent">
  <h3>Mythology</h3>
  <p><a href="https://thesourceaid.w3spaces.com/Greek-Mythology.html" role="button">Greek Mythology</a>
<br>
<a href="https://thesourceaid.w3spaces.com/Mesopotamian-Mythology.html" role="button">Mesopotamian Mythology</a>
<br>
<a href="https://thesourceaid.w3spaces.com/Hindu-Mythology.html" role="button">Hindu Mythology</a>
</div>
</p>
<div id="4 Checks" class="tabcontent">
  <h3>Checking sources</h3>
  <ol>
<li><details><summary>Check Domain</summary>
<p><strong>.COM</strong>/These sources need to have
Named author
Info about the author's background/expertise
Date of publication
Works Cited
<br>
<strong>.ORG</strong>/Be critical of purpose
"The organization... has the purpose of ... This is/is not credible because ..."
More biased purpose = less credible (but not necessarily bad)
Less breadth of information = less credible
<br>
<strong>Other Domains</strong>/<strong>.GOV</strong> (government)
Official domain that cannot be used outside of actual government sources = credible
<br>
<strong>.EDU</strong> means education
Be critical of author (professor, graduate student, student work, etc.)
Professor = more credible
Student work = less credible</p></details>

</li>
<li><details><summary>Check Website</summary>
Author is an expert or information about them is available
<br>
Transparency of sponsors/partners = more credible
<br>
Updated = more credible
<br>
Clearly organized with easy-to-find publication information = more credible
<br>
Logical organization to information and arguments = more credible</details></li>

<li><details><summary>Facts</summary>
Valuable works cited = more credible
<br>
Peer-reviewed notation = more credible
<br>
Embedded links redirecting to the same source = less credible
<br>
Less breadth of information = less credible
<br>
More repetitive information/only one point of view = less credible
<br>
Use of evidence = more credible
<br>
Conclusions are logical = more credible</details></li>

<li><details><summary>Check Emotions</summary>
More emotional is not necessarily a bad thing, but you need to be aware of these manipulations
<br>
Emotional appeals without evidence = less credible
<br>
Strong language without evidence = less credible</details></li>

</div>
<div id="Crediting" class="tabcontent">
  <h3>Citation Tools</h3>
  <p><a href="https://www.mybib.com/tools/mla-citation-generator" role="button">Automatic Citation mla-citation-generator</a>
</div>
</p>
</body>
</div>
  

<script>
function openCity(evt, cityName) {
  var i, tabcontent, tablinks;
  tabcontent = document.getElementsByClassName("tabcontent");
  for (i = 0; i < tabcontent.length; i++) {
    tabcontent[i].style.display = "none";
  }
  tablinks = document.getElementsByClassName("tablinks");
  for (i = 0; i < tablinks.length; i++) {
    tablinks[i].className = tablinks[i].className.replace(" active", "");
  }
  document.getElementById(cityName).style.display = "block";
  evt.currentTarget.className += " active";
}
</script>
</body>
</html>

